CS214 Project 2 - compare

Names:
- Victor Olivo (vmo32)
- Yasser Zguiouar (yz1474)

Testing Plan

The program was tested on the Rutgers iLab environment using a variety of files and directories to validate each requirement of the assignment.

1. Basic functionality
Two explicit files were compared.

Example:

echo "spam eggs bacon spam" > a.txt
echo "spam spam eggs" > b.txt
./compare a.txt b.txt

Verified that the program prints a single JSD comparison with the correct format.

2. Recursive directory traversal
Created a directory with nested subdirectories.

mkdir testdir
mkdir testdir/sub
echo "hello world hello" > testdir/a.txt
echo "hello hello world" > testdir/sub/b.txt
./compare testdir

Verified that files in subdirectories were included.

3. Hidden file handling
Created hidden files and directories.

echo "hidden content" > testdir/.hidden.txt
mkdir testdir/.secret

Verified that files beginning with . were skipped.

4. Error handling
Created an unreadable file.

touch testdir/bad.txt
chmod 000 testdir/bad.txt
./compare testdir

Verified that the program prints Permission denied using perror() and continues processing other files.

5. Tokenization tests
Tested punctuation and apostrophes.

echo "I can't understand thieves' cant." > p1.txt
echo "i cant understand thieves cant" > p2.txt
./compare p1.txt p2.txt

Verified that punctuation is ignored and words are treated case-insensitively.

6. Hyphen handling
Tested words containing hyphens.

echo "state-of-the-art model" > h1.txt
echo "state-of-the-art model" > h2.txt
./compare h1.txt h2.txt

Verified that hyphens are treated as word characters.

7. Known JSD example
Used the example from the assignment:

echo "hi there hi there" > f1.txt
echo "hi hi out there" > f2.txt
./compare f1.txt f2.txt

Verified that JSD is approximately 0.3945.

8. Edge cases
Tested:
- single file input
- empty file
- explicit file combined with directory argument
- duplicate file detection

Verified that the program reports an error if fewer than two files are collected.

9. Memory testing
The program was tested using Valgrind:

valgrind --leak-check=full ./compare testdir

Valgrind reported 0 memory leaks and 0 invalid memory accesses.
